etymologies: late Middle English; earliest use found in Geoffrey Chaucer (c1340–1400), poet and administrator. From tithe + -er

notes.text: In early use frequently with preceding qualifying adjective, as false, small, true, etc.

etymologies: late 19th century; earliest use found in Black and White. Origin uncertain; perhaps a variant of dither

definitions: A state of nervous excitement, agitation, or anxiety. Chiefly in (all) in a tither, (all) of a tither.
